   has actually been caught by the process step designed to catch it,
   because that step never ran to completion.

2. SIGNIFICANT — CONTRACTS.md's own worked example contradicts its own
   stated invariant for the segmented-abstract shape. The doc states
   "Display char range of `display_text`... 0-indexed, end-exclusive
   (`display_abstract[char_start:char_end] === display_text`)". For the
   example's segment index 1, `display_text` = "Prior work has shown
   mixed results in Fig. 2, e.g. reduced uptake vs. controls." — verified
   length 79 characters (`len()` checked directly) — but the example
   gives `char_start: 12, char_end: 92`, i.e. a 80-char span, one too
   long, so the pinned example does not actually satisfy the pinned
   invariant. Any agent (1D writing the tokenizer, or a tester writing
   an assertion) that copies this example verbatim as a reference/golden
   value will encode the off-by-one. Not a code bug (CONTRACTS.md is
   docs-only per its own text) but a real inconsistency in the one
   cross-team artifact whose entire purpose is to prevent two agents
   from silently diverging.

3. MINOR — fixtures/tokenizer/abbreviation_corpus.json sets up a
   disambiguation problem it doesn't document a solution strategy for:
   case `abbreviation_at_true_sentence_end` requires splitting after
   "et al." when followed by a capitalized new sentence ("Chen et al.
   The mechanism..."), while case `titles_and_approx` requires NEVER
   splitting after "Dr." even though it is always followed by a
   capitalized proper name ("Dr. Alvarez led..."). A tokenizer using the
   simplest heuristic that satisfies the et-al case (split when the next
   token is capitalized) will fail the Dr. case, and vice versa —
   correct behavwior requires per-abbreviation-class rules (title
   abbreviations exempted from the capitalization check entirely) that
   the fixture/README doesn't call out. This is a legitimate hard
   requirement for whoever builds 1D, not a defect in Tier 0's
   deliverable, but worth flagging now since both 1D and 2D will
   independently discover it.

